entry.title: arc: Fix calculation of required free space for ARCVM /data migration
entry.content:
ARCVM /data migration converts sparse files in the migration source into

non-sparse files. As a result, the migrated /data will require more

space than the space allocated for pre-migration /data when there are

sparse files in the migration source, and the pre-migration free space

check needs to take this into account as well. This CL fixes the

calculation of required free space so that it additionally requires the

space for the increase of /data size throughout the migration.

entry.title: Directly launch Native Host executables on Windows
entry.content:
Previously, launching an extension's native host executable on Windows

would launch cmd.exe, setting the input and output pipes to Named Pipes

used to share JSON messages between the extension and the Host app.



While this worked in most cases, it would fail in cases where:



1) the system disabled access to cmd.exe,

2) cmd.exe was configured to always elevate,

3) COMSPEC was pointed at something other than cmd.exe, or

4) a special character (e.g. &) was in the path to the Native

Host program.



This CL changes the calling pattern for the common case where the Native

Host manifest points at an executable. In such cases, Chrome will now

directly launch the executable and pass file streams to its stdin and

stdout, avoiding the invocation of cmd.exe altogether.



For legacy compatibility (e.g. a Native Host can be implemented via a

python script launched by a batch file), the old path using cmd.exe

remains for use when the Native Host target is not an executable.



This change was previously landed and backed out due to compatibility

issues with some Native Hosts. It is now behind an off-by-default

feature flag to enable experimentation and evangelism.



BUG=1445763,335558,387233,387228

entry.title: cast: Adjust stats unit test
entry.content:
This CL changes the `CastRuntimeHistogramFlattenerTest` suite to use a

temporary `base::StatisticsRecorder` to provide isolation from other

stats possibly emitted by other tests in the process (and vice-versa).

process lifetime, causing this suite to fail in `SetUp()`.

PA-E shim setup, which would yield a polluted histogram state anyway.

accessible by other pages, which will be useful to figure out how

much we need to care about potentially synchronously accessible vs

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Misc batch execution optimizations and cosmetic changes
entry.content:
- Enables batch model execution by default. This way the potential

  performance improvement vs. individual execution can be observed

  in pre-stable experiment without making the experimentation more

  complex.

- If the model is not available or any of the model inputs cannot

  be generated from the signals, calls the completion callback with

  an empty vector of prediction scores so the ACController can exit

  processing the output early.

- Reserves vector capacity and avoids populating them and making

  copies where possible.

- Computes `stripped_destination_url` for the eligible matches only.

- Groups only eligible matches for rescoring, reducing the size of

  the std::map by half.

- Improves comments and variable names for clarity.

entry.title: Fixed toolbar capture ignoring optional button updates
entry.content:
Toolbar captures are skipped if the toolbar's state hasn't changed. The

container for toolbar state is PhoneCaptureStateToken. This class

keeps a reference to ButtonData, which represents the state of the

optional toolbar button and it uses standard equality checks to

determine of the optional button has changed. This works if the

button is updated with a new instance of ButtonData, but many providers

reuse the same instance, just changing its properties. This results in

button updates (e.g. when changing the button type from settings) not

triggering a new toolbar capture.



This CL updates ButtonData to implement its hashCode() method, this gets

used by PhoneCaptureStateToken to determine if the same instance of

ButtonData changed its attributes.

entry.title: sensors: Reset |last_{raw,rounded}_reading_| when a sensor stops.
entry.content:
Once set, |last_{raw,rounded}_reading_| were never reset, even when a

sensor stopped and the shared buffer was required to be zeroed. This

caused problems for sensors whose reporting mode is ON_CHANGE (which are

the only ones that actually use |last_{raw,rounded}_reading_|) as

starting a sensor again and attempting to set a reading too close to 0

would fail even if it should not.



Fix it by making sure |last_{raw,rounded}_reading_| are reset when an

empty SensorReading is passed, and make the intention more clear by

refactoring the code a bit: move the actual writing to |reading_buffer_|

into a separate function and split UpdateSharedBuffer() into separate

code paths for regular writes and for resetting the buffer.
